    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Structures, typically relatively substantial and often with with columns, arches, a roof, hangings, and other decorations used to shelter a catafalque or bier, especially those used to designate the prestige or rank of the deceased. It is first seen in Medieval funerary services as a temporary structure and in permanent monuments.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046846/BHA, Authority file (2003-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000011851/Dictionary of the Middle Ages (1982-1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046892/Grove Art Online (2003-2008)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Medieval funerary structures consisting of lofty arched frameworks of wood or metal with a number of posts or columns supporting one or more steeply pitched roofs. They were used to support the body of a deceased person of high rank. The form was a precursor to the catafalque.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Middeleeuwse rouwgebouwen bestaande uit hoge boogconstructies van hout of metaal met een aantal stijlen of zuilen die een of meer steile daken ondersteunen. Ze werden gebruikt om het stoffelijk overschot van een hooggeplaatst persoon in te plaatsen. De vorm was een voorloper van de katafalk.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>用於遮護靈柩台或棺架之結構物，通常十分堂皇，常有圓柱、拱、簷頂、掛簾以及特為顯示往生者名望和地位而吊掛之其他飾物。最早見於中古世紀為喪葬儀式所豎立之紀念碑或臨時搭建的結構物。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bauwerk, im allgemeinen relativ bedeutend und oft mit Säulen, Bögen, einem Dach, Behängen und anderen Ausschmückungen versehen, genutzt um einen Katafalk oder eine Totenbahre zu schützen, insbesondere solche, die genutzt werden, um das Ansehen oder die Stellung des Verstorbenen anzuzeigen. Das Trauergerüst ist erstmals von mittelalterlichen Begräbnissen als vorübergehendes Bauwerk und dauerhaftes Denkmal bekannt.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
